{
  "slug": "abigail-late-night-with-the-devil-and-the-10-best-horror-mov",
  "title": "‘Abigail,’ ‘Late Night With the Devil,’ and the 10 Best Horror Movies of 2024 … So Far",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Chris Ryan",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2024-04-23",
  "runtimeMin": 83,
  "format": "Sean and Chris run their twice-a-year horror check-in with reviews of Late Night With the Devil and Abigail. Amanda Dobbins drops in to recount Imaginary scene by scene, then it's a dig through the 2024 indie pile and an argument over which non-horror director should try the genre.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The state of horror in 2024",
      "note": "strong but aimless",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Night Swim",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Sean's pick for the softly underrated hit of the year so far, sitting around $35M. The show already did a whole episode explaining it to Amanda."
        },
        {
          "title": "Immaculate",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "The Sydney Sweeney nun horror, which Sean notes did solid business for a very small movie."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Late Night With the Devil’",
      "note": "the found-footage talk show",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Late Night with the Devil",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Colin and Cameron Cairns' film, framed as a recovered tape of a 1977 Halloween talk-show broadcast that goes wrong live on air. David Dastmalchian's first lead role gets raves from both. Chris watched it alone late at night house-sitting in Portland and loved the mood; Sean felt the third act lost him. Their shared complaint: the movie stacks trauma and a secret-society conspiracy on top of an idea that was already gripping, a 'hat on a hat.'"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Abigail’",
      "note": "they kidnapped the wrong girl",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Abigail",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Radio Silence's (Matt Bettinelli-Olpin and Tyler Gillett) vampire movie for Universal, a soft remake of Dracula's Daughter. A kidnapping crew (Melissa Barrera, Dan Stevens, Kathryn Newton, Kevin Durand, Giancarlo Esposito, and Angus Cloud in his final role) grabs a girl (Alisha Weir) who turns out to be a vampire. Both find it enjoyable but forgettable; the marketing gave the twist away, and the third-act gore should have been the whole movie's energy. The film is dedicated to Angus Cloud."
        },
        {
          "title": "Ready or Not",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "The earlier Radio Silence film Sean keeps comparing Abigail to, and likes more: a leaner one-house horror-comedy with explosive gore."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dracula's Daughter",
          "year": 1936,
          "note": "The 1930s Universal horror Abigail loosely remakes, though the finished film backpedals on the Dracula mythology."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "‘Imaginary,’ recapped for Chris",
      "note": "Elvira Jr. grinds tape",
      "guest": "Amanda Dobbins on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Imaginary",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Amanda drops in to narrate the whole Blumhouse creepy-teddy-bear movie for Chris, who refused to watch it. DeWanda Wise plays a stepmom whose youngest, Alice, befriends a bear named Chauncey found bricked up in the basement; the bear sends the kid on a scavenger hunt. Everyone agrees on the one great scene: a child therapist films the session and reveals 'Jessica, there is no bear.' Then, per Amanda, it goes completely off the rails into a Beetlejuice-style imaginary world. She would not recommend it, aside from that one scene."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Digging through the 2024 indie pile",
      "note": "concept vs. execution",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The First Omen",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Arkasha Stevenson's prequel, which Chris calls a dead-on recreation of 1970s horror that doesn't feel dated. Sean is high on Stevenson as a filmmaker; the claw-through-the-birth-canal image gets the running Biden-campaign-poster bit going."
        },
        {
          "title": "Infested",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Sébastien Vaniček's French spider horror, heading to Shudder: an apartment-block siege Sean likens to Attack the Block with spiders, with an Aliens-y team-in-the-cave feel. Bug horror always works on him; he recommends it, spiders and all. Vaniček is reportedly attached to the next Evil Dead."
        },
        {
          "title": "Lovely, Dark, and Deep",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Georgina Campbell as a forest ranger alone at a remote station. Strong concept and opening (people vanishing in national parks) that Sean feels gets lost in dream logic, his least favorite horror crutch."
        },
        {
          "title": "Somewhere Quiet",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Marin Ireland and Jennifer Kim in an off-season Cape Cod thriller: a kidnapping survivor grows paranoid about her husband and his cousin. Effective use of the setting, though Sean wishes it had a little more life in it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Stopmotion",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Robert Morgan's debut with Aisling Franciosi as the daughter of a tyrannical stop-motion animator. After the mother dies, the creations start to come to life and torment her. Sean calls it the flipside of Imaginary, impressive as a small debut even if it frays near the end."
        },
        {
          "title": "Blackout",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Larry Fessenden's werewolf movie. Sean started it but hadn't finished; it's the hook for a long appreciation of Fessenden as the godfather of mumblecore-plus-a-monster indie horror."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Seeding",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Barnaby Clay's canyon horror with Kate Lyn Sheil, about a man trapped at the bottom of a desert canyon, harassed by feral children. Sean's pitch: what if Denis Villeneuve made The Hills Have Eyes. Well made and creepy but, he says, not actually scary."
        },
        {
          "title": "Arcadian",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Ben Brewer's post-apocalyptic creature film with Nicolas Cage and Jaeden Martell, about a father and two sons surviving a nightly monster siege. Worth it for the creature design: clearly digital but with a snapping, clapping ferocity Sean hadn't seen before, on an obviously tiny budget."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Who should make a horror movie",
      "note": "plus the rest of the year",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "MaXXXine",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Sean's most-anticipated: Ti West's third Maxine film, out July 5, even if it plays more like an L.A. thriller than a horror movie."
        },
        {
          "title": "Alien: Romulus",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Fede Alvarez's entry, which both think looks terrifying. Sean is coming back from vacation just to podcast about it and plans to dodge all pre-release buzz. He wants extreme terror, not xenomorph timeline."
        },
        {
          "title": "Longlegs",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Oz Perkins's Nic Cage serial-killer movie with a great trailer."
        },
        {
          "title": "Cuckoo",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Tilman Singer's follow-up to Luz, with Dan Stevens and Hunter Schafer. Sean's heard it's extremely strange, which tracks."
        },
        {
          "title": "Nosferatu",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Robert Eggers' remake, which they frame as the year's big test: the one Eggers gets to scare everyone with."
        },
        {
          "title": "Smile 2",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Coming in the fall and, in a lean Paramount year, one of the studio's most important releases. Reportedly leaning more psychological than the first, which worries them a little."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
